Definition: A 4-amino-1,2-oxazolidin-3-one that has <stereo>R</stereo> configuration. It is an antibiotic produced by <ital>Streptomyces garyphalus</ital> or <ital>S. orchidaceus</ital> and is used as part of a multi-drug regimen for the treatment of tuberculosis when resistance to, or toxicity from, primary drugs has developed. An analogue of <stereo>D</stereo>-alanine, it interferes with bacterial cell wall synthesis in the cytoplasm by competitive inhibition of <stereo>L</stereo>-alanine racemase (which forms <stereo>D</stereo>-alanine from <stereo>L</stereo>-alanine) and  <stereo>D</stereo>-alanine<em_dash/><stereo>D</stereo>-alanine ligase (which incorporates <stereo>D</stereo>-alanine into the pentapeptide required for peptidoglycan formation and bacterial cell wall synthesis).
Imidazole substituted at position 4 by a methyl group.

A member of the class of triazoles that is 1<element>H</element>-1,2,4-triazole substituted by an amino group at position 3. Used to control annual grasses and aquatic weeds (but not on food crops because it causes cancer in laboratory animals). Its use within the EU was banned from September 2017 on the grounds of potential groundwater contamination and risks to aquatic life; there have also been concerns about its endocrine-disrupting properties.
A hydroxycoumarin that is coumarin in which the hydrogen at position 4 is replaced by a hydroxy group.
An optically active form of 4-hydroxytryptophan having <stereo>L</stereo>-configuration.
A nucleoside pentaphosphate that is adenosine in which a hexahydrogen pentaphosphate is attached at the 5' position.
A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate having 5-fluorouracil as the pyrimidine component.
A monocarboxylic acid that is butyric acid bearing a 2-thienyl group at position 4.
An  acetate ester obtained by the formal condensation of acetic acid with propanol.
A monocarboxylic acid that is valeric acid substituted by a phenyl group at the <locant>delta</locant>-position.
The (<stereo>R</stereo>)-enantiomer of rolipram.
A pyrimidone that is uracil in which positions 1, 5, and 6 are substituted by ethoxymethyl, isopropyl, and phenylsulfanyl groups, respectively.
An organofluorine compound that is uridine bearing a fluoro substituent at position 5 on the uracil ring.
The purine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is AMP monomethylated on <element>N</element><smallsup>6</smallsup>.
A member of the class of imidazoles that is 1<element>H</element>-benzimidazole in which the hydrogen at position 5 is substituted by a methyl group.
A member of the class of 2,6-diaminopurines that is 9<element>H</element>-purine in which the hydrogens at positions 2 and 6 are replaced by amino groups.
A  triazolopyrazine that exhibits  hypoglycemic activity.
Flavin-adenine dinucleotide (FAD) in which the hydrogen at position 6 of the benzo[<ital>g</ital>]pteridinedione moiety is substituted by a hydroxy group.
A 1,2-diacyl-<ital>sn</ital>-glycero-3-phosphocholine(1+) in which both acyl groups are palmitoyl.
Purine bearing a methyl substituent at position 6.
A bicyclic structure comprising a pyrazole ring fused to a hydroxy-substituted pyrimidine ring.
A member of the class of benzamides obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 2-fluorobenzoic acid with the amino group of 2-amino-4,5,6,7-tetrahydro-1-benzothiophene-3-carbonitrile.

A fatty acid ester that is mevastatin carrying an additional methyl group on the carbobicyclic skeleton. It is used in as an anticholesteremic drug and has been found in fungal species such as <ital>Aspergillus terreus</ital> and <ital>Pleurotus ostreatus</ital> (oyster mushroom).
Guanosine substituted at the purine 8-position by a hydroxy group. It is used as a biomarker of oxidative DNA damage.

A 17-membered macrocyclic lactam that incorporates a phenol and a substituted indole moiety. It includes a <stereo>R</stereo>-hydroxy group at position 11 and a (3-methyl-2-oxopentanoyl)amino group at position at position 18 with a <stereo>S</stereo>-methyl group. It acts as a proteasome inhibitor and is obtained from <ital>Apiospora montagnei</ital> Sacc. TC 1093, isolated from a soil sample.
An <element>N</element>-acetyl-<stereo>D</stereo>-galactosamine having <stereo>alpha</stereo>-configuration at the anomeric centre.
A 2',3'-cyclic purine nucleotide that is AMP in which the hydroxy groups at the 2' and 3' positions have been converted to the corresponding cyclic phosphate.
A 2-polyprenylphenol in which the polyprenyl chain contains 8 prenyl units; major species at pH 7.3.
An <element>N</element>-acylglycine where the acyl group is specified as acetyl.
A <element>C</element>-nitro compound that is the <element>N</element>-(4-nitrobenzyl),<element>N</element>-phosphonomethyl derivative of 5-aminovaleric acid.
An <stereo>D</stereo>-arabinose 5-phosphate that is <stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-arabinofuranose attached to a phospahte group at position 5.
A member of the class of phenylacetic acids that is phenylacetic acid in which the phenyl grup is substituted at the <ital>para</ital>- position by a nitro group.
A member of the class of phenanthrolines that is 2,7-phenanthroline substituted at position 9 by a 4-hydroxyphenyl group.
An anthraquinone that is anthracene in which positions 9 and 10 have been oxidised to carbonyls.
A adenosine 5'-phosphate that is the 2'-<element>O</element>-methyl derivative of adenosine 5'-monophosphate.
A guanidinium ion resulting from the protonation of the guanidinyl group of <stereo>L</stereo>-arginine amide.
<stereo>L</stereo>-Norleucine substituted at C-6 with a borono group.
An <element>N</element>-acetyl-<stereo>L</stereo>-amino acid that is <stereo>L</stereo>-arginine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is replaced by an acetyl group.
Adenine substituted with a methyl group at position N-9.
<stereo>L</stereo>-Norleucinate substituted at C-6 with a borono group.
A primary amine compound having benzyl as the <element>N</element>-substituent. It has been isolated from  <ital>Moringa oleifera</ital> (horseradish tree).
A non-proteinogenic <locant>alpha</locant>-amino acid that is cyclopentane substituted at position 1 by amino and carboxy groups.
A primary alcohol that is ethanol substituted by a 2-ethoxyethoxy group at position 2.

A group, formally derived from acetic acid by dehydroxylation, which is fundamental to the biochemistry of all forms of life. When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.

A <stereo>alpha</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-Gal<ringsugar>p</ringsugar>A-(1<arrow>right</arrow>4)-<stereo>D</stereo>-Gal<ringsugar>p</ringsugar>A in which the anomeric hydroxy group has <stereo>alpha</stereo>- configuration.
A cycloamylose composed of six <stereo>alpha</stereo>-(1<arrow>right</arrow>4) linked <stereo>D</stereo>-glucopyranose units.
An  aminonaphthalenesulfonic acid fluorophore with a structure consisting of ethylenediamine substituted on the nitrogens with acetyl and 5-sulfonyl-1-naphthyl groups.
A <stereo>D</stereo>-fructofuranose 1,6-bisphosphate with an <stereo>alpha</stereo>-configuration at the anomeric position.
The cation obtained by protonation of the imine nitrogen of (5<stereo>S</stereo>)-5-methyl-<stereo>L</stereo>-arginine.
A one-carbon compound whose unique structure renders it capable of acting as a derivative of hydrazine, guanidine or formamide.
An organic anion that is a borate diester derived from a furanose and acts a universal signal molecule mediating intra- and interspecies communication among bacteria.
A <stereo>D</stereo>-allopyranose with a <stereo>beta</stereo>-configuration at the anomeric position.
An anhydrohexose derivative that is the 1,6-anhydro-derivative of <element>N</element>-acetyl-<stereo>beta</stereo>-muramic acid.
Anthracene substituted at C-9 by a propionic acid group and at C-10 by a methyl group.
An optically active form of 2-aminoheptanoic acid having <stereo>L</stereo>-configuration.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of adenosine 5'-monophosphate (AMP) obtained by selective protonation at position N1 on the purine moiety.
A  substituted aniline that is a benzene ring substituted with an amino group at position 1 and a trifluoromethyl group at position 4.
The <stereo>S</stereo>-enantiomer of adrenaline.
A  primary amino compound that is 1,3-thiazole substituted by an amino group at position 2.
A steroid that consists of androstane having double bonds at positions 1 and 4 and two keto groups at positions 3 and 17.
A dinitrophenol having the nitro groups at the 2- and 5-positions.
A methoxybenzoic acid substituted with a methoxy group at position C-4.
A dihydroxyanthraquinone that is 1,2-dihydroxyanthraquinone compound carrying an additional sulfo substituent at the 3-position. The monosodium salt is the biological stain 'alizarin red S'.
A <stereo>L</stereo>-arabinopyranose with a <stereo>beta</stereo>-configuration at the anomeric position.
A 1,3-thiazole that is 4,5-dihydro-1,3-thiazole substituted by an amino group at position 2.
A trisaccharide composed of three <stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-galactose units joined by (1<arrow>right</arrow>4)-linkages.

An aryloxypyrimidine having a 4,6-diphenoxypyrimidine  skeleton in which one of the phenyl rings is cyano-substituted at C-2 and the other carries a 2-methoxy-1-(methoxycarbonyl)vinyl substituent, also at C-2. An inhibitor of mitochondrial respiration by blocking electron transfer between cytochromes b and c<smallsub>1</smallsub>, it is used widely as a fungicide in agriculture.

A phosphonic ester that is the monoethyl ester of phosphonic acid.  A fungicide used (as its aluminium salt) for various horticultural crops used to control a range of diseases including <ital>Phytophthora</ital>, <ital>Pythium</ital> and <ital>Plasmopara </ital>.
An optically active form of 3-aminoadipic acid having (<stereo>S</stereo>)-configuration.
An <element>N</element>-methylated dihydro acridine carrying carbonitrile and <element>N</element>-carboxyethylcarbamoyl substituents at C-9.
A water-soluble buffer substance used for the preparation of the biochemical and biological buffer solutions; p<ital>K</ital><smallsub>a</smallsub> = 6.8 at 20 <degree/>C.
A member of the class of pyrazoles that is an immunomodulator used for treatment of rheumatoid arthritis, Crohn's disease and psoriasis.
A  bicine that is a Good's buffer substance, p<ital>K</ital><smallsub>a</smallsub> = 8.35 at 20 <degree/>C.

A carotenone that consists of <greek>beta</greek>,<greek>beta</greek>-carotene-4,4'-dione bearing two hydroxy substituents at positions 3 and 3' (the 3<stereo>S</stereo>,3'<stereo>S</stereo> diastereomer). A carotenoid pigment found mainly in animals (crustaceans, echinoderms) but also occurring in plants. It can occur free (as a red pigment), as an ester, or as a blue, brown or green chromoprotein.
An <element>N</element>-acetyl-<stereo>L</stereo>-amino acid that is <stereo>L</stereo>-alanine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is replaced by an acetyl group.
A  benzoate ester metabolite of cocaine formed by hydrolysis of the methyl ester group, catalysed by carboxylesterases.
A <stereo>D</stereo>-fructopyranose in which the anomeric centre has <stereo>beta</stereo>-configuration.
A <locant>beta</locant>-amino acid that is butanoic acid substituted by an amino group at position 3 and a hydroxy group at position 4.
A diamino acid that is heptanoic acid substituted by amino groups at positions 3 and 7 respectively (the 3<stereo>S</stereo> stereoisomer).
A carboxamidine that is benzene carrying an amidino group.
A <stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-galactopyranosyl-(1<arrow>right</arrow>4)-<stereo>D</stereo>-galactopyranose with a <stereo>beta</stereo>-configuration at the reducing end anomeric center.
A pyrimidone that is uracil which is substituted by a 2-hydroxyethoxymethyl group at position 1 and a benzyl group at position 5.
A thioester that is a synthetic analogue of thiamine obtained by acylative cleavage of the thiazole ring and <element>O</element>-phospohorylation.

A quaternary ammonium ion obtained by the formal condensation of the carboxy group of butyric acid with the thiol group of thiocholine. It is used as a reagent for determination of butyrylcholinesterase activity.
A benzene-derived hexacarboxylic acid in which each carbon of benzene carries a carboxy substituent.
A member of the class of  hydroquinones that is benzene-1,4-diol substituted by <ital>tert-</ital>butyl groups at position 2 and 5.
An amino sugar that is <stereo>alpha</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucose in which the 2 and 6-hydroxy groups are replaced by amino groups.
An <element>N</element>-acetylmannosamine having pyranose form and <stereo>alpha</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-configuration.
An <stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucoside in which the anomeric hydrogen of <stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucopyranose is substituted by an octyl group.
A but-2-enoic acid with a <stereo>trans</stereo>- double bond at C-2. It has been isolated from <ital>Daucus carota</ital>.
A member of the class of benzamides obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-phenoxybenzoic acid with the amino group of (pyridin-2-yl)methylamine.
A quaternary ammonium ion in which the substituents on nitrogen are methyl (three) and carboxymethyl.
A pyrroline consisting of 2-pyrroline having methyl and carboxy substituents at positions 4 and 5 respectively.
A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is the 6-oxo derivative of UMP.
A biopterin in which the 1,2-dihydroxypropyl group has (1<stereo>S</stereo>,2<stereo>R</stereo>)-configuration.

A butanediol that is butane in which one hydrogen of each of the methyl groups is substituted by a hydroxy group. A colourless, water-miscible, viscous liquid at room temperature (m.p. 16<degree/>C) with a high boiling point (230<degree/>C), it is mainly used for the production of other organic chemicals, particularly the solvent oxolane (also known as tetrahydrofuran or THF).
A bacteriopheophytin consisting of bacteriochlorophyll <ital>a</ital> with two hydrogen atoms replacing the magnesium centre.
A member of the class of benzyl alcohols that is benzyl alcohol substituted at the <ital>para</ital>-position by a nitro group.
A benzoate ester obtained by the formal condensation of benzoic acid with benzyl alcohol. It has been isolated from the plant species of the genus <ital>Polyalthia</ital>.
The (<stereo>R</stereo>)-enantiomer of 2-benzylsuccinic acid.

A buffer substance useful for calibration of glass electrodes and for the preparation of the biochemical and biological buffer solutions; p<ital>K</ital><smallsub>a</smallsub> = 6.46 at 25 <degree/>C.
A straight chain alkane consisting of 14 carbon atoms.

A furoic acid that is furan-3-carboxylic acid substituted by a methyl group at position 4, a propyl group at position 5 and a 2-carboxyethyl group at position 2. It is a potent uremic toxin that has been found to accumulate in human serum of patients with chronic kidney diseases.
A <locant>beta</locant>-hydroxy ketone that is butan-2-one substituted by a hydroxy group at position 4.
A substituted diphenylfuran in which two <element>N</element>-ethylamidino substituents are located at the two <ital>para</ital>-positions on the phenyl rings.
The 1<element>H</element>-tautomer of benzimidazole.

An <element>N</element>-acylpyrrolidine obtained by formal condenstion of the carboxy group of <stereo>L</stereo>-proline and the secondary amino group of (<stereo>R</stereo>)-pyrrolidine-2-carboxylic acid.
A purine 2'-deoxyribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate having 6-<element>O</element>-benzylguanine as the nucleobase.
The simplest member of the class of benzophenones, being formaldehyde in which both hydrogens are replaced by phenyl groups.
A member of the class of phenylureas that is urea in which one of the hydrogens of each amino group is replaced by a phenyl group. It is present in coconut milk (<ital>Cocos nucifera</ital>).
A steroid sulfate that is cholesterol substituted by a sulfoxy group at position 3.
A propanoate ester of ethanol.
A quarternary ammonium cation having one dodecyl and three methyl substituents around the central nitrogen.
A member of the class of phosphonic acids that is phosphonic acid having a butyl group attached to the phosphorous atom.

A member of the class of pyrazoles that is 1<element>H</element>-pyrazole which is substituted at positions 1, 3 and 5 by 4-sulfamoylphenyl, trifluoromethyl and <ital>p</ital>-tolyl groups, respectively. A cyclooxygenase-2 inhibitor, it is used in the treatment of arthritis.

A  non-proteinogenic <stereo>L</stereo>-<stereo>alpha</stereo>-amino acid that is <stereo>L</stereo>-glutamic acid in which one of the <locant>gamma</locant>-hydrogens is substituted by a carboxy group.
A 2',3'-cyclic pyrimidine nucleotide that is CMP in which the hydroxy groups at the 2' and 3' positions have been converted to the corresponding cyclic phosphate.

A member of the class of phenylureas that is urea in which a hydrogen attached to one nitrogen is replaced by a cyclohexyl group and a hydrogen attached to the other nitrogen is replaced by a <ital>p</ital>-iodophenyl group.
A pyrimidone that is thymine in which the hydrogen at position 6 is substituted by a 1,3-dihydroxyisobutyl group.

A monocarboxylic acid the structure of which is that of butyric acid substituted with a phenyl group at C-4.  It is a histone deacetylase inhibitor that displays anticancer activity. It inhibits cell proliferation, invasion and migration and induces apoptosis in glioma cells. It also inhibits protein isoprenylation, depletes plasma glutamine, increases production of foetal haemoglobin through transcriptional activation of the <greek>gamma</greek>-globin gene and affects hPPAR<greek>gamma</greek> activation.
The (9<stereo>Z</stereo>,12<stereo>Z</stereo>)-stereoisomer of cholesteryl octadeca-9,12-dienoate.
The hydroxypolyether that is octaethylene glycol in which one of the hydroxy groups is substituted by dodecyloxy.

An <stereo>L</stereo>-cysteinyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxylic acid group of <stereo>L</stereo>-cysteine with methanol. It is used (as the hydrochloride salt) as a mucolytic for the treatment of respiratory disorders associated with productive cough.

An <element>N</element>-acyl-<stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-galactosylsphingosine having a sulfo group at the 3-position on the galactose ring and (15<stereo>Z</stereo>)-tetracos-15-enoyl as the <element>N</element>-acyl group.
The <stereo>D</stereo>-enantiomer of pipecolic acid.

A chromanol that is chroman-6-ol which is substituted at positions 2, 3, and 4 by <ital>p</ital>-(2-pyrrolidin-1-ylethoxy)phenyl, <ital>p</ital>-hydroxyphenyl, and methyl groups, respectively (the 2<stereo>R</stereo>,3<stereo>R</stereo>,4<stereo>S</stereo> diastereoisomer).
An enal consisting of propene having a formyl group at the 1-position.
A medium-chain fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (pentylsulfanyl)acetic acid.
A pyrroledicarboxylic acid that is pyrrole-2,5-dicarboxylic acid in which the hydrogens at positions 3 and 4 have been replaced by indol-3-yl groups.
A cysteine derivative consiting of <stereo>L</stereo>-cysteine carrying an <stereo>S</stereo>-oxy-substituent.

A 3<stereo>beta</stereo>-hydroxy-<greek>Delta</greek><smallsup>5</smallsup>-steroid that is desmosterol in which the double bond at position 24-25 has been oxidised to the corresponding epoxide (the 24<stereo>S</stereo> diastereoisomer). It is an oxysterol agonist of the liver X receptor.
A member of the class of pyrazoles that is 1<element>H</element>-pyrazole carrying 1,4-benzodioxane-6-yl and 5-ethyl-2,4-dihydroxyphenyl substituents at positions 4 and 5 respectively.
A cyclohexanedione carrying oxo substituents at positions 1 and 2.

An organic chloride salt that is the monochloride salt of crystal violet cation. It has been used in creams for the topical treatment of bacterial and fungal infections, being effective against some Gram-positive bacteria (notably <ital>Staphylococcus</ital> species) and some pathogenic fungi (including <ital>Candida</ital> species) but use declined following reports of animal carcinogenicity. It has also been used for dying wood, silk, and paper, as well as a histological stain.

A non-proteinogenic <stereo>L</stereo>-<stereo>alpha</stereo>-amino acid that is <stereo>L</stereo>-methionine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the amino group bas been replaced by a carboxy group.
A cysteine derivative consisting of <stereo>L</stereo>-cysteine carrying an <element>S</element>-hydroxy-substituent.
A cysteine derivative consiting of <stereo>L</stereo>-cysteine carrying two <stereo>S</stereo>-oxy-substituents.

An aryl sulfate that is 4-nitrocatechol in which the hydroxy group that is <ital>meta</ital> to the nitro group has been converted to the corresponding hydrogen sulfate. It is used (commonly as its dipotassium salt) as a chromogenic substrate for sulphatase.
A cellotriose with a <stereo>beta</stereo>-configuration at the anomeric position.
A substituted diphenylfuran in which two amino(cyclopropylamino)methyl substituents are located at the two <ital>para</ital>-positions on the phenyl rings.
A member of the class of furans that is furan which is substituted by aminomethyl and pyridy-3-yl groups at positions 2 and 5 respectively.
A straight-chain alkane with 10 carbon atoms.
An organic disulfide obtained by formal oxidative dimerisation of 4-thiopyridine.
A pyrimidine 2',3'-dideoxyribonucleoside 5'-triphosphate having thymine as the nucleobase.
A 1,2-diacyl-<ital>sn</ital>-glycerol where both acyl groups are specified as octadecanoyl.
An <locant>alpha</locant>,<locant>omega</locant>-dicarboxylic acid that is the 1,8-dicarboxy derivative of octane.
A quinolinium ion comprising decane in which one methyl hydrogen at each end of the molecule has been replaced by a 4-amino-2-methylquinolin-1-yl group.

A fluorinated steroid that is 9-fluoropregna-1,4-diene substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 11, 17 and 21, a methyl group at position 16 and oxo groups at positions 3 and 20. It is a synthetic member of the class of  glucocorticoids.
A member of the class of benzyl alcohols that is benzyl alcohol substituted by fluoro groups at positions 2 and 3 respectively.

A uronic acid that is <stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucuronic acid in which the hydroxy group at position 4 and the hydrogen at position 5 have been eliminated with the introduction of a double bond between positions 4 and 5.
A tertiary amine oxide that is the <element>N</element>-oxide of <element>N</element>,<element>N</element>-dimethyldecan-1-amine.
An <ital>ortho</ital>-fused bicyclic arene comprising of benzene and cyclopentene rings.
A quaternary ammonium ion that is a depolarising muscle relaxant whose structure comprises a decane-1,10-diamine core in which each amino group carries three methyl substituents.
A dihydroxyphenylacetic acid having the two hydroxy substituents located at the 3- and 4-positions. It is a metabolite of dopamine.
A fluoroamino acid that is ornithine substituted by a difluoromethyl group at position 2.
A phosphonic ester that is the diethyl ester of phosphonic acid.
The (2<stereo>S</stereo>,3<stereo>S</stereo>)-stereoisomer of taxifolin.
A monocarboxylic acid that is acetic acid where the methyl hydrogens have been replaced by two phenyl groups respectively.

An optically active tricarboxylic acid that consists of 1,4,7,10-tetraazacyclododecane bearing three carboxymethyl substituents at positions 1, 4 and 7 as well as an (<stereo>R</stereo>)-2-hydroxypropyl group at position 10.
A natural product found in <ital>Actinomadura roseola</ital>.
An anthracycline cation resulting from the protonation of the amino group of 4'-epidoxorubicin.
A member of the class of pyrimidine ribonucleosides that is zebularine in which the double bond between positions 3 and 4 of the pyrimidone ring has been reduced to a single bond.
A dinitrophenol having the nitro groups at the 2- and 4-positions.
A member of the class of 1,4-benzoquinones that is 1,4-benzoquinone in which all four hydrogens are substituted by methyl groups.
An <stereo>L</stereo>-lysine derivative with a dansyl group at the <element>N</element><smallsup>6</smallsup>-position.
An <locant>omega</locant>-amino fatty acid that is dodecanoic acid in which one of the terminal amino hydrogens has been replaced by an amino group.
A 1,2-di-octadecadienoyl-<ital>sn</ital>-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the double bonds in each fatty acyl group are at positions 9 and 12 and have <stereo>Z</stereo> configuration.
A tetracarboxylic acid that is an optically active twelve-membered tetraazamacrocycle having a carboxymethyl group attached to each of the nitrogens and a 4-nitrobenzyl group at the 2-position.
An oxodicarboxylic acid that is glutaric acid which is substituted by oxo groups at positions 2 and 4.
A 1,3-diazepanone ring with two 4-(hydroxymethyl)benzyl groups as substituents at positions N-1 and N-4, two benzyl groups at C-4 and C-7, and two hydroxy groups at C-5 and C-6 respectively.

The isomer of 7,8-diaminononanoic acid having (<stereo>R</stereo>)- and (<stereo>S</stereo>)- configurations at C-7 and C-8, respectively; an intermediate in the biosynthetic pathway of biotin. As biotin is made exclusively in plants and microorganisms, both the chemical structure and biosynthetic enzymes of DAPA are targets for the development of herbicides and antimicrobial drugs.

An amino trisaccharide consisting of <stereo>alpha</stereo>-<stereo>L</stereo>-fucose, <stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-galactose and <element>N</element>-acetyl-<stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucosamine residues joined by sequential (1<arrow>right</arrow>2)- and (1<arrow>right</arrow>4)-linkages.
Synonyms: human blood group H type 2 trisaccharide

Definition: The <stereo>L</stereo>-enantiomer of threitol.

A hydroxy steroid that consists of 5<stereo>beta</stereo>-cardanolide having a double bond at the 20(22)-position as well as hydroxy groups at the 3<stereo>beta</stereo>-, 12<stereo>beta</stereo>- and 14<stereo>beta</stereo>-positions. It has been isolated from the plant species of the genus <ital>Digitalis</ital>.
The <stereo>D</stereo>-enantiomer of 2-aminohexanoic acid.
An optically active form of lactic acid having (<stereo>R</stereo>)-configuration.
A ketoaldonic acid phosphate consisting of 3-deoxy-<stereo>alpha</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-<stereo>manno</stereo>-oct-2-ulosonic acid carrying a phospho substituent at position 8.

A tetracarboxylic acid that is an optically active twelve-membered tetraazamacrocycle having a carboxymethyl group attached to each of the nitrogens and a 4-substituted benzyl group at the 2-position.

A C-terminal boronic acid petide that is <element>N</element>-acetyl-<stereo>D</stereo>-phenylalanyl-<stereo>L</stereo>-prolyl-<stereo>L</stereo>-arginine in which the C-termnal carboxy group has been replaced by a borono (-B(OH)<smallsub>2</smallsub>) group. A thrombin (Factor IIa) inhibitor, thereby acting as an anticoagulant.

A 16<stereo>alpha</stereo>-hydroxy steroid that is estriol in which the hydroxy group at position 17 has been epimersied from <stereo>beta</stereo>- to <stereo>alpha</stereo>- configuration. It is a metabolite of estradiol and a selective estrogen receptor beta (ER-<greek>beta</greek>) agonist.

A glycosyloxyisoflavone that is  daidzein attached to a <stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucopyranosyl residue at position 7 via a glycosidic linkage. It is used in the treatment of alcohol dependency (antidipsotropic).

A 5<stereo>beta</stereo>-cardenolide that is 5<stereo>beta</stereo>-cardanolide with hydroxy substituents at the 3<stereo>beta</stereo>- and 14<stereo>beta</stereo>-positions and double bond unsaturation at C(20)-C(22).

A trihydroxyanthraquinone that is 9,10-anthraquinone which is substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 1, 3, and 8 and by a methyl group at position 6. It is present in the roots and barks of numerous plants (particularly rhubarb and buckthorn), moulds, and lichens. It is an active ingredient of various Chinese herbs.

A phosphonic acid consisting of 1-cyclopentyluracil having a phosphomethoxy group at position 2 on the cyclopentyl ring with (1<stereo>R</stereo>,2<stereo>R</stereo>)-<stereo>trans</stereo>-stereochemistry.
A flavan-3,3',4',5,5',7-hexol having (2<stereo>R</stereo>,3<stereo>R</stereo>)-configuration.

An optically active form of 2-(hydroxymethyl)piperidine-3,4,5-triol having 2<stereo>R</stereo>,3<stereo>R</stereo>,4<stereo>R</stereo>,5<stereo>S</stereo>-configuration.

A member of the class of ureas that is urea in which one of the hydrogens is replaced by a hydroxy group. An antineoplastic used in the treatment of chronic myeloid leukaemia as well as for sickle-cell disease.
An aromatic ether having phenyl and 2-methylsulfonamido-5-nitrophenyl as the two aryl groups.
A  3-nitrotyrosine comprising <stereo>L</stereo>-tyrosine having a nitro group at the 3-position on the phenyl ring.
A quaternary ammonium ion in which the substituents on nitrogen are methyl (three) and 4-oxopentyl.

A fatty acid methyl ester obtained from the formal condensation of methanol and nonanoic acid; a colourless liquid with a fruity odour, used in perfumes and flavours, and for medical research.

The (<stereo>S</stereo>)-enantiomer of 2-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid. Derived from the metabolism of the branched-chain amino acids, it belongs to the 2-hydroxycarboxylic acid group of amino acid metabolites.

An organosulfinic acid that is benzenesulfinic acid in which the hydrogen at position 2 has been replaced by a 2-hydroxyphenyl group.
A peroxide-bridged anthracene substituted at the bridgeheads with methyl and carboxyethyl groups.
A retinoid that is <stereo>all-trans</stereo>-retinol in which the hydrogens at position 4 have been replaced by an oxo group.
A dicarboxylic acid monoamide of glutaric acid containing benzene and oxidopiperidine moieties; a transition state analogue hapten used to elicit catalytic antibodies 5C8 and 14B9.
An <element>N</element>-acylamino acid consisting of 6-aminohexanoic acid bearing an <element>N</element>-(4-hydroxy-3-nitrophenyl)acetyl substituent.

A primary aliphatic amine that is ethylamine substituted by two methyl groups at position 1.
A uridine 5'-phosphate that is the 2'-<element>O</element>-methyl derivative of uridine 5'-monophosphate.

A polycyclic ether that is produced by several species of dinoflagellates, and is known to accumulate in both marine sponges and shellfish.  A polyketide, polyether derivative of a C<smallsub>38</smallsub> fatty acid, it is one of the primary causes of diarrhetic shellfish poisoning (DSP). It is a potent inhibitor of specific protein phosphatases and is known to have a variety of negative effects on cells.
A polyether that consists of undecane in which the carbon atoms at positions 3, 6 and 9 are replaced by oxygen atoms.
A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is CMP monomethylated at position O-2'
The <stereo>L</stereo>-enantiomer of ornithinium(2+).

A derivative of octanoic acid carrying a <locant>beta</locant>-oxo group; a possible metabolite of 2-octynoic acid.
The hydroxamate of phosphonoacetic acid.
A 1,2-diacyl-<ital>sn</ital>-glycero-3-phosphocholine having a dodecanoyl group at the 1-position and a pentacosanoyl group at the 2-position.
A pyridinedicarboxylic acid carrying carboxy groups at positions 2 and 4.

A tetrahydroxytetrahydrofuran in which the hydroxy groups are located at positions 2, 3, 4, and 4 and which is substituted by a methyl group at position 2 (the 2<stereo>R</stereo>,4<stereo>S</stereo> diastereoisomer).

A polyatomic cation consisting of four phenyl groups attached to a central phosphonium.
